# Extending Classes 🧬

Use the colon `:` syntax.

```csharp
public class Animal {
    public void Eat() { Console.WriteLine("Eating"); }
}

// Dog inherits from Animal
public class Dog : Animal {
    public void Bark() { Console.WriteLine("Woof"); }
}
```
`Dog` now has both `Eat()` and `Bark()`.

# Calling Parent 📞

Use `base` to access members of the parent class, especially constructors.

```csharp
public class Person {
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public Person(string name) { Name = name; }
}

public class Student : Person {
    public int Grade { get; set; }
    // Pass name to parent constructor
    public Student(string name, int grade) : base(name) {
        Grade = grade;
    }
}
```

# Changing Behavior 🎭

Unlike C++, C# requires explicit keywords for polymorphism.

1.  **`virtual`**: Use in Base class to say "This can be changed".
2.  **`override`**: Use in Child class to say "I am changing this".

```csharp
class Animal {
    public virtual void Speak() => Console.WriteLine("...");
}
class Dog : Animal {
    public override void Speak() => Console.WriteLine("Bark");
}
```

# Partial Blueprints 🧩

An **Abstract Class** cannot be instantiated. It can have abstract methods (no code) that children MUST implement.

```csharp
public abstract class Shape {
    // Must be implemented by child
    public abstract double Area();

    // Normal method
    public void Display() { Console.WriteLine("Shape"); }
}
```

# Pure Contracts 📜

An **Interface** contains only method signatures. A class can implement **multiple** interfaces (solving multiple inheritance).

```csharp
interface IMovable {
    void Move();
}

class Car : IMovable {
    public void Move() { Console.WriteLine("Vroom"); }
}
```
Naming convention: Start with `I`.

